column1: # executed_on: 'Darwin-21.6.0-Darwin Kernel Version 21.6.0: Mon Aug 22 20:19:52 PDT

column8: predicted_definition

column2: X-linked intellectual disability due to GRIA3 anomalies
column8: A X-linked intellectual disability that has material basis in mutation in the GRIA3 gene on chromosome Xq25 resulting in anomalies of the nervous system.
A sub type of Biliary Atresia that presents along with other anticipated abnormalities or syndromes
An instance of lethal multiple congenital anomalies/dysmorphic syndrome that is derived from MultipleCongenitalAnomaliesDysmorphicSyndrome.

column2: fatal infantile hypertrophic cardiomyopathy due to mitochondrial complex I deficiency
column8: A subtype of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, a disease of the heart muscle, that is caused by a deficiency in mitochondrial complex I. It is marked by severe cardiac hypertrophy and can be fatal, particularly in infants.

column3: A new leukoencephalopathy, the CACH syndrome (Childhood Ataxia with Central nervous system Hypomyelination) or VWM (Vanishing White Matter) was identified on clinical and MRI criteria. Classically, this disease is characterized by (1) an onset between 2 and 5 years of age, with a cerebello-spastic syndrome exacerbated by episodes of fever or head trauma leading to death after 5 to 10 years of disease evolution, (2) a diffuse involvement of the white matter on cerebral MRI with a CSF-like signal intensity (cavitation), (3) a recessive autosomal mode of inheritance, (4) neuropathologic findings consistent with a cavitating orthochromatic leukodystrophy with increased number of oligodendrocytes with sometimes ``foamy'' aspect.
column8: A type of leukodystrophy characterized by the loss of white matter in the brain.

column3: Autosomal recessive form of complex hereditary spastic paraplegia.
column8: Autosomal recessive form of complex hereditary spastic paraplegia.

column3: A corneal dystrophy (disease) that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A corneal dystrophy that presents as part of a syndrome.

column3: A rare combined T and B cell immunodeficiency with a predisposition to lymphoproliferative syndrome. It is characterized by persistent symptomatic EBV-viremia and hypogammaglobulinemia variably presenting with fever, lymphadenopathy and systemic inflammatory conditions including hepatitis, pneumonia and sepsis. It may be associated with lymphoma, hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis, and aplastic anemia.
column8: A lymphoproliferative syndrome that follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern.
A disease of the epidermis.

column2: anomaly of puberty or/and menstrual cycle
column8: An abnormal condition affecting the puberty or menstrual cycle in females.
A specific form of acrodysostosis that affects multiple hormones and is characterized by mandibulofacial dysostosis, acrofacial dysostosis, and hereditary otorhinolaryngologic diseases.

column2: 46,XX disorder of sex development induced by maternal-derived androgen
column8: A 46,XX disorder of sex development that is induced by an excess of maternal-derived androgen. This can affect the development of the fetus, leading to atypical sexual development.
Cap Myopathy 2 is a subtype of Cap Myopathy

column2: intestinal disease due to vitamin absorption anomaly
column8: A rare disease characterized by a disruption of intestinal absorption and vitamin transport leading to a malabsorption syndrome.

A rare type of lymphoma that forms in the skin and can spread to the blood, bone marrow, and internal organs. It is called “primary” because it originates in the skin, rather than spreading to the skin from another place in the body.

Teratogenic Pierre Robin syndrome refers to a sequence of developmental abnormalities induced by environmental exposure during pregnancy. It is characterized by anomalies such as mandibular hypoplasia (micrognathia), displacement of the tongue base (glossoptosis), and cleft palate. Otorhinolaryngologic complications may also occur.

A very rare, complex subtype of hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by a slowly progressive spasticity of lower limbs (resulting in difficulty walking) and intellectual disability. Additional signs and symptoms may include peripheral neuropathy, amyotrophy, and cerebellar signs (like nystagmus or dysarthria).

column2: progressive myoclonic epilepsy with neuroserpin inclusion bodies
column8: Progressive myoclonic epilepsy with neuroserpin inclusion bodies is a genetic disease caused by an accumulation of a mutant form of neuroserpin. It is characterized by neurodevelopmental regression, cognitive milestone loss and progressive myoclonus epilepsy.
A neoplasm of nervous cell origin. They are generally benign and proliferate by expansion. However, they may invade surrounding structures and rarely metastasize.
An anomaly of the border of the eyelid.

column2: congenital muscular dystrophy with cerebellar involvement
column8: A form of muscular dystrophy that begins in infancy or early childhood and is characterized by severe muscle weakness, loss of independent ambulation, intellectual disability and involvement of the cerebellum in the brain.

column2: retinal ciliopathy due to mutation in the RPGR gene
column8: A retinal ciliopathy in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the RPGR gene.
An inherited tumor (disease) that is located in the digestive tract.
A genetic condition characterized by the symptoms of obesity, where the cause of the condition is a mutation in an individual's genes.

column2: congenital absence/hypoplasia of fingers excluding thumb
column8: A rare, non-syndromic, terminal transverse limb reduction defect characterized by absence or underdevelopment of the fingers excluding the thumb.
A tumor that forms in the peritoneum, the thin layer of tissue that covers the abdomen and several organs in the abdomen.

column2: 46,XX disorder of sex development induced by androgens excess
column8: 46,XX disorder of sex development induced by androgens excess refers to a group of rare, genetic disorders of sex development where exposure to excessive levels of androgens leads to masculinization (virilization) of the external genitalia in phenotypically normal female individuals. This results in varying degrees of undervirilization and/or ambiguity of external genitalia, ranging from clitoromegaly to partial and complete fusion forming a urogenital sinus, penoscrotal hypospadias and/or labioscrotal fusion. Internal mullerian structures are typically present and normal.

column2: retinal ciliopathy due to mutation in Usher gene
column8: A retinal ciliopathy caused by mutations in any of the Usher genes.
A malformation in the structure of the respiratory system or thoracic area.

column2: transposition of the great arteries and conotruncal cardiac anomaly
column8: A congenital heart disease that involves a malformation of the heart's great arteries and conotruncal region.

column3: A urogenital tract malformation that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A urogenital tract malformation that is part of a larger syndrome.

column3: An inherited metabolic disease that is has its basis in the disruption of glycerol metabolic process.
column8: An inherited metabolic disorder that has its basis in the disruption of glycerol metabolic process.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of myotilin
column8: Any qualitative or quantitative protein defects in neuromuscular diseases that involves a mutation in the MYOT gene.

column3: A hypothyroidism that is part of a larger syndrome.
column8: A group of signs, symptoms, and clinicopathological characteristics that often include hypothyroidism as a component.

column2: anomaly of the secretory and excretory apparatus of the lacrimal system
column8: Anomaly characterized by abnormalities in the lacrimal system, which exhibit as rare disorders affecting the tear-secreting and tear-excreting structures.
A metabolic disorder characterized by the body's inability to break down fatty acids and ketones due to an enzyme deficiency.
A disease that disrupts lens induction in a camera-type eye causing developmental defects.

Regional variant of Guillain-Barré syndrome is a rare type of Guillain-Barré syndrome that affects only certain areas of the body. The symptoms and progression of the disease can vary significantly depending on the specific region affected.
A visceral malformation of the liver, biliary tract, pancreas or spleen that is part of a larger syndrome.
A movement disorder that affects the peripheral nerves and is not present at birth but develops later in life.
A structural abnormality of the esophagus.

column2: AP4-related intellectual disability and spastic paraplegia
column3: A disorder that presents with spastic paraplegia and intellectual disability in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the AP4B1 gene.
column8: A rare genetic disease characterized by intellectual disability, microcephaly, growth retardation, and spastic paraplegia, often with additional abnormalities. It is caused by mutations in the AP4 genes.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of protein O-mannose beta1, 2N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase
column8: A defect that's a subtype of qualitative or quantitative defects of protein involved in O glycosylation of alpha dystroglycan.

column2: qualitative or quantitative defects of glucosamine (UDP-N-acetyl)-2-epimerase/N-acetylmannosamine kinase
column8: A metabolic disease that has material basis in mutations in the GNE gene causing a deficiency of an enzyme necessary for the synthesis of sialic acid.

column3: An inflammatory disease involving a pathogenic inflammatory response in the brain.
column8: A disease causing inflammation in the brain.
A congenital condition characterized by malformation of the ear, and of the mouth and jaw on one side of the face.

column2: 46,XY disorder of sex development due to isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency
column3: 46,XY disorder of sex development due to isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency is a rare disorder of sex development due to reduced 17,20-lyase activity that affects individuals with 46,XY karyotype and is characterized by ambiguous external genitalia, including micropenis, perineal hypospadias, bifid scrotum, cryptorchidism, and a blind vaginal pouch. Blood pressure and electrolytes are normal whilst hormonal investigations show normal basal and stimulated levels of cortisol, and low basal and stimulated androgen levels.
column8: 46,XY disorder of sex development due to isolated 17,20-lyase deficiency is a type of Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia Due To 17 Alpha Hydroxylase Deficiency.
